# {{lb|en|intransitive}} (often followed by ''[[up]]'') To stop [[sleep]]ing.
#: ''I '''woke''' up at four o'clock this morning.''
#* '''1898''', {{w|J. Meade Falkner}}, {{w|Moonfleet}} Chapter 4
#*: How long I slept I cannot tell, for I had nothing to guide me to the time, but '''woke''' at length, and found myself still in darkness.
# {{lb|en|transitive}} (often followed by ''[[up]]'') To make somebody stop sleeping; to [[rouse]] from sleep.
#* Bible, Zech. iv. 1
#*: The angel {{...}} came again and '''waked''' me.
#: ''The neighbour's car alarm '''woke''' me from a strange dream.''
# {{lb|en|transitive|figurative}} To put in motion or action; to arouse; to excite.
#* {{rfdate||and other bibliographic particulars, eg, title of work, page, url, full name of author}} {{w|John Milton}}
#*: lest fierce remembrance '''wake''' my sudden rage
#* {{rfdate||and other bibliographic particulars, eg, title of work, page, url, full name of author}} {{w|J. R. Green}}
#*: Even Richard's crusade '''woke''' little interest in his island realm.
# {{lb|en|intransitive|figurative}} To be excited or roused up; to be stirred up from a dormant, torpid, or inactive state; to be active.
#* {{rfdate||and other bibliographic particulars, eg, title of work, page, url, full name of author}} {{w|John Milton}}
#*: Gentle airs due at their hour / To fan the earth now '''waked'''.
#* {{rfdate||and other bibliographic particulars, eg, title of work, page, url, full name of author}} {{w|Keble}}
#*: Then '''wake''', my soul, to high desires.
# To lay out a body prior to [[burial]] in order to allow family and friends to pay their [[last respects]].
# To watch, or sit up with, at night, as a dead body.
# To be or remain awake; not to sleep.
#* Bible, Eccles. xlii. 9
#*: The father '''waketh''' for the daughter.
#* {{rfdate||and other bibliographic particulars, eg, title of work, page, url, full name of author}} {{w|John Milton}}
#*: Though wisdom '''wake''', suspicion sleeps.
#* {{rfdate||and other bibliographic particulars, eg, title of work, page, url, full name of author}} {{w|John Locke}}
#*: I cannot think any time, '''waking''' or sleeping, without being sensible of it.
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} To be alert; to keep watch
#* Command unto the guards that they diligently '''wake'''.
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} To sit up late for festive purposes; to hold a night revel.
#* {{rfdate||and other bibliographic particulars, eg, title of work, page, url, full name of author}} {{w|William Shakespeare}}
#*: The king doth '''wake''' to-night, and takes his rouse, / Keeps wassail, and the swaggering upspring reels.

